      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why I-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>I appears nine times in the Scrabble bag — tied with A as the most common vowel. That frequency means you'll always have I available for plays, and understanding how to leverage it separates casual players from competitive ones. I's power lies in three areas: the prefix game, the -ING bingo engine, and high-value pairings.</p>
      <p>Prefix plays (IN-, IM-, IR-, IL-) turn existing board words into new ones. If your opponent plays "EXACT," you can extend it to "INEXACT" for a huge scoring turn. These prefix extensions often span premium squares that were previously unreachable, multiplying your score dramatically.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing I-Words</h2>
      <p>I is abundant — so the strategy isn't about hoarding it, but about using it efficiently. Here's how:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Prefix extension plays:</strong> IN-, IM-, IR-, and IL- extend existing words. FORM → INFORM, PROPER → IMPROPER, LEGAL → ILLEGAL. Each extension scores for the full new word, not just the added letters.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Hold I for -ING bingos:</strong> I is one-third of the ING bingo engine. With I + N + G plus four other tiles, you're positioned for a 50-point bonus play. Don't waste I on low-value plays if ING is forming.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair I with X for IBEX/IXIA:</strong> IBEX (13 pts) and IXIA (11 pts) are compact I+X words that hit premium squares effectively. INDEX (13 pts) and INFIX (15 pts) use the IN- prefix plus X for extra value.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Dump excess I tiles early:</strong> With 9 I tiles in the bag, drawing 2-3 is common. Words like IAMB, IRIS, and IBIS use multiple vowels to clear rack clogs without sacrificing position.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>-IZE suffix plays:</strong> ITEMIZE (18 pts), IONIZE (15 pts), IDOLIZE (17 pts) — the -IZE ending combines I with Z for consistent double-digit scoring from common word roots.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The Prefix Power of I</h2>
      <p>I-prefixes are among the most productive in Scrabble. They transform opponents' words into your scoring opportunities and often reach premium squares that the original word didn't cover:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>IN- words:</strong> INFORM, INFLUX, INDEX, INFIX, INQUEST — the most versatile I-prefix with thousands of valid extensions</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>IM- words:</strong> IMMUNIZE, IMPUGN, IMBIBE, IMPROV — useful when the next letter is B, M, or P</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>IR- words:</strong> IRONWORK, IREFUL — less common but catches opponents off guard</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Managing I-Heavy Racks</h2>
      <p>Drawing multiple I tiles is inevitable given their frequency. Here's how to handle it without losing momentum:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Two I's on rack:</strong> Look for words with double-I like BIKINI, ALIBI, CRISIS — they exist but are uncommon. Usually better to play one I and keep the other for next turn.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Three+ I's:</strong> Exchange at least one. The rack imbalance isn't worth struggling through — take the short-term loss for better future draws.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>I + other vowels:</strong> If I is clogging with A or E, words like IDEA, IOTA, and AERIE help dump vowels while keeping consonant options open.</span></li>
      </ul>

